This paper is about event and relation extraction in biomedical text mining, which involves natural language processing and machine learning techniques. Therefore, the most likely arXiv CS sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language), which covers topics related to natural language processing and computational linguistics. 

The paper also proposes a novel approach that uses multi-head attentions and convolutions, which are common techniques in deep learning and neural networks. This suggests that the paper could also belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) or cs.LG (Machine Learning), which cover topics related to artificial intelligence and machine learning. 

Furthermore, the paper evaluates its approach on benchmark biomedical corpora, which involves information retrieval and evaluation techniques. This suggests that the paper could also belong to cs.IR (Information Retrieval), which covers topics related to information retrieval and search engines. 

Finally, the paper's approach involves modeling the interaction between features extracted by multiple attention heads, which suggests that it could also belong to cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing), which covers topics related to neural networks and evolutionary algorithms.
